latestPosts.caption:
“ Irene Cattaneo’s work unravels the expected, distorting familiar forms to reconfigure reality into a poetic landscape of reversals. Borrowing its title from Lewis Carroll’s 1871 novel, Through the Looking-Glass draws viewers into a world where meaning is never fixed—words shift, identities blur, and rules dissolve as quickly as they are established. Language and literature are central to Cattaneo’s practice—titles become word games, subtle reversals, or playful distortions that mirror the physical transformations in her work.
Written just a decade before the Upper East Side brownstone housing this installation was built, Carroll’s novel opens with Alice stepping through a mirror in a Victorian drawing room, entering a space where logic dissolves and perception is upended. Cattaneo’s sculptural works inhabit a similar world of contradiction and illusion: branching green-patinated stalks of cast bronze seem to sprout and sway from above, while a solid marble cloud anchors itself to the ground below; metal appears to melt and flow, while sculpted onyx emits light rather than obstructing it. Chess serves as a recurring motif, both an object of play and an illusion of control. In Carroll’s text, its structure appears logical yet proves arbitrary. Alice advances across the board not by master-ing the game, but by disrupting it. Poignantly, she becomes a queen not by partnering with a king, but by moving on her own terms. Ascending her own way seems to be the only way. In Through the Looking-Glass, Cattaneo extends this logic, creating a world where transformation is a mode of being—one in which material, meaning, and movement are in constant flux. “

latestPosts.caption:
Thank you for including my works in PAVONE  @ashlee_harrison ; a show co-curated by @etiennemacret within the beautiful space @maisonrocherparis 
This October, from the 12th to the 20th, PAVONE brought the spirit of the Parisian salon into a contemporary context, engaging in a dialogue between art and design while exploring themes of reverie, myth, and the ethereal.
REVERIE
Timed alongside the Centre Pompidou’s centennial celebration of surrealism, PAVONE invites visitors into a state of reverie. Following the spirit of the traditional salon’s encouragement of intellectual exploration, this theme delves into the subconscious and the uncanny. The curated selection evokes a dreamlike environment where the natural world meets the imagination, bending reality into the fantastical, blending the known with the mysterious.
MYTH
Myth is represented in the title PAVONE, which alludes to the peacock as a symbol of the god Argus Panoptes, the all-seeing giant with a hundred eyes. In Greek mythology, Hera transferred Argus’s eyes to the tail of the peacock, symbolizing watchfulness, beauty, and intrigue. This symbol becomes the guiding force behind the exhibition, which threads through time, examining how historical periods influence one another and become layered in the work. Visitors will be immersed in a world where mythologies are reinterpreted, and the boundaries between art, design, and environment blur.
THE ETHEREAL
The ethereal alludes to light and space works that interact with the texture and shine of the objects in the room, celebrating the forward-looking and avant-garde. Showcasing works that challenge traditional boundaries, this theme pushes the limits of art and design, engaging with contemporary expressions of innovation and conceptual thought.

latestPosts.caption:
🇮🇹 LITTLEGIG HOMO FABER ARTIST 🇮🇹 

Irene Cattaneo is an Italian artist based in Venice whose practice embraces sculptures, functional art and design of spaces. After earning degrees in Economics and Management from Bocconi University and an MA in Design Management from Central Saint Martins and London College of Fashion, she created her brand “re/ne,” which showcased illuminated art pieces and led to her interest in light as a medium. Moving to Venice, @_icat_ immersed herself in glassmaking, resulting in her ongoing series “Clouds and Coulds,” which blends traditional Murano techniques with contemporary design. She has exhibited at “The Venice Glassweek,” Spazio Musa in Turin, Di Donna Galleries in New York and Nomad Capri. In 2024, she created a site-specific glass installation at Samaritaine in Paris and opened her solo show “Meteomorphosis” at Lo Studio - @NadjaRomain in Venice.

Irene has a work on display in Homo Faber 2024: The Journey of Life, and will also lead an experience at her solo show.
